ce:section.ce:para:
The commercial anti-blue light and UV test card were used to further investigate the ability of pure PVA film and different CND-OBFs to block harmful blue light (405 nm, 10.6 W/m2) and UV rays (796 μW/cm2) from sunlight. The experiments clearly demonstrate that CND-OBFs exhibit a good ability in blocking short wavelength light (Video S1 and Video S2). Balsa wood, white maple and basswood were used to investigate the use of CND-OBFs to protect wood from UV damage. Wood samples were coated with pure PVA film and different CND-OBFs and then irradiated with UV light (340 nm, 80 W) for 90 h. As shown in Fig. 5
                     a-c, there was significant darkening of the color of the surface of uncoated wood and wood covered with pure PVA film, indicating that pure PVA film didn't block UV rays. CND-OBFs, however, markedly suppressed changes in the color of the wood surface, with films containing larger amounts of CNDs having a more obvious effect. After UV irradiation, the ΔL* and ΔE* values of all three types of wood were determined (Fig. 5d and e). The absolute values of ΔL and ΔE approached 0 as the proportion of CNDs in the film was increased, reflecting smaller and smaller changes in the color of the wood surface. Therefore, we proposed the following mechanism for CND-OBFs protecting wood. CND-OBFs with a low content of CNDs absorbed some short wavelength photons, and then the long wavelength light obtained by light conversion and the unabsorbed short wavelength light radiated to the wood surface, thereby decreasing direct radiation of short wavelength light and slowing down of wood color darkening. When the content of CNDs was increased (≥15.7 %), the short wavelength photons were completely absorbed by CND-OBFs, so that a part of the excited electrons were released through non-radiative transitions; while others returned to the ground state through the radiative transition, generating long wavelength light radiation onto the wood surface (Fig. 5f), achieving complete blocking (suppression) short wavelength light, thus protecting the wood from damage caused by short wavelength light. These results indicate that CND-OBFs have potential applications in protecting wood against damage caused by short wavelength light, and that the extent of blocking of short wavelength light can be controlled by adjusting the proportion of CNDs in the film. A radar map (Fig. 6
                     ) was used to compare CND-OBF (15.7 %) with reported UV-protective materials (Table S2) in terms of environmental friendliness of raw materials, simplicity of process flow, transparency, sustainability, resistance to UV light and the proportion of CNDs [25,55,60,61]. The results confirmed that CND-OBF (15.7 %) not only had the ability to efficiently block UV, but also had the advantages of good transparency and simple preparation process, low amount of CNDs and rich carbon source (Table S2). CNDs with concentration-dependent emission are, therefore, expected to have many practical applications in preventing damage caused by short wavelength light.
